NOTES ON RED BURGUNDY The 1963 vintage provided some useful, but not outstanding Burgundies—they will not be ’62s, 61s or ’59s—and only about 20% of the wine that Beaujolais produced is worth exporting. But the Burgundian grower can be consoled in the knowledge that his 62s were bountiful and of good quality, particularly among the whites—that his 61s can easily prove to be the best vintage since the war; wines of balance and fruitiness. long- lived and the kind of wine that no wine aficionado can afford to ignore. We can forget 1960 and lift our glasses in thanks to the Burgundian proprietor for his 1959s, which showed their fruit and charm at birth, and are now proving to be an absolute delight for

consuming now and perhaps for another five years ahead.
